    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-05-18T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-05-18T11:00:00-05:00" n="333"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d333">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.116 Lard/15: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-18T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 18, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 18—1:55 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>91. For the Department of Agriculture from Steere.<note n="18" xml:id="d333fn18"
                        >Loyd V. Steere, Agricultural Attaché.</note>
                </p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“For Wheeler, Foreign Service. Officially advised German preliminary import
                        quotas American lard metric tons May 2,616, June 1,071, July 883, which
                        equivalent 35, 29, 28 percent, respectively, of average imports
                        corresponding months 1931–33 basis cabled March 16. Danish quotas same
                        months 1,109, 954, 1,034 tons according to <hi rend="italic">Land
                            Brugraadets Meddelelser</hi> or 64, 65. 65 percent same basis. This
                        appears indicate clear discrimination against American lard. We are
                        attempting to ascertain quotas extended certain other countries and are
                        consulting with Embassy and the Commercial Attaché regarding further steps.
                        [Steere.”]</p>
                </quote>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
